<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">tongue of land called by the french the Anse and by the Indians Keeyw<span class="DelHand-author">ie</span><span class="AddHand-author">ay</span>nan Or the way made straight by means of a Portage<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  From the bottom of the bay to the extreme point of the tongue is <span class="DelHand-author">good</span> <span class="AddHand-author">at least</span> fifteen leagues and the general breadth not less than five<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  About three leagues from the entrance of the bay there is <span class="AddHand-author">a</span> Small Peninsula which when doubled you enter a bason of two miles in circumference which can hardly be exulted for beauty or Safety<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The soil is very fine on the Peninsula and here the Indians have a Summer Village and Cultivate some Maize.  The eastern Side of <span class="DelHand-author">Isthmus</span> <span class="AddHand-author">the Tongue</span> is a continued line of freestone mostly of a brick Colour always perpendicular but of Various heights and intersected by Several Sandy bays; Off the extreme point there is an Island two or three miles from the Shore which the Vessels generally make coming from Camanitiquia: and near the enterance of the Bay there are two Small Islands Round which there is good Anchorage which enables a Vessel to hold what she has already made in case of a Northeasterly gale<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Pique of Nipagon which projects considerably into the Lake and is <span class="DelHand-author">ne</span><span class="AddHand-author">ex</span>actly opposite to Keeywaynan forms a kind of <span class="DelHand-author">straight</span> <span class="AddHand-author">strait</span> and is the narrowest part of the <span class="AddHand-author">main body <span class="DelHand-author">of</span> of the</span> Lake not being more than thirty or forty leagues over<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  From Grand Island to Michipaquaton on the North Shore it is at least eighty leagues broad and about thirty leagues to the Southwest of Keeyway<span class="AddHand-author">nan</span></p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[27]</span></p>

